1. The K-net debate properly began at the 2006 meeting of the SMT in Los Angeles, 
where Michael Buchler gave the paper that later appeared in Music Theory Online 13.2. See Michael Buchler, “ Reconsidering Klumpenhouwer Networks ,” Music Theory 
Online 13.2 (2007); 
and the responses in the next volume: Scott Murphy, “ Considering Network 
Recursion and Bartók’s ‘Fourths,’ ” Music Theory Online 13.3 
(2007); 
Gretchen Foley, “ The Efficacy of K-Nets in Perlean Theory ,” Music Theory Online 13.3 (2007); 
Henry Klumpenhouwer, “ Reconsidering Klumpenhouwer Networks: a Response ,” Music Theory Online 13.3 (2007); 
Catherine Losada, “ K-nets and Hierarchical Structural Recursion: Further 
Considerations ,” Music Theory Online 13.3 (2007); 
Catherine Nolan, “ Thoughts on Klumpenhouwer Networks and Mathematical Models: 
The Synergy of Sets and Graphs ,” Music Theory Online 13.3 
(2007); Shaugn O’Donnell, “ Embracing Relational Abundance ,” Music Theory Online 13.3 (2007); 
Philip Stoecker, “ Without a Saftey (k)-Net ,” Music Theory Online 13.3 (2007); Dmitri Tymoczko, “ Recasting K-nets ,” Music Theory Online 13.3 (2007).
